<div><h1>GREP - pocket references</h1></div>
<div><br></div>
<div>-Grep with regular expression - general syntax</div>
<div>	grep [options] [regexp] [filename]</div>
<div><br></div>
<div>-Characters for regex:</div>
<div>	normal characters or literals</div>
<div>	special characters like * or meta character</div>
<div>	escape sequence: allows you to use special character as normal character or to detect special word boundary such as space or tab</div>
<div>-Back stick: wrap a command —&gt run that command first and take the results —&gt then grep for that results</div>
<div>	+grep `whoami` filename</div>
<div><br></div>
<div>-Double quote: allows return value of environment variable as input for arep</div>
<div>	+grep &quot$HOME&quot filename</div>
<div><br></div>
<div><br></div>
<div><br></div>
<div><br></div>

<div><br></div>
<div>grep has rules of precedence for processing:</div>
<div>	+Repetition is processed before concatenation.</div>
<div>	</div>
<div>Grep can be chained</div>
<div>	+cat filename | grep regexp | grep regexp2</div>
<div><br></div>
<div>However, “chaining” grep commands is inefficient most of the time —&gt use regular expression to combine several conditions into a single search.</div>
<div>When a search can be accomplished using fewer commands or with fewer decisions having to be made, the more efficiently it will behave. For small files, per-</div>
<div>formance isn’t an issue, but when searching through gigabyte-sized logfiles, performance can be an important consideration.</div>
<div><br></div>
<div><br></div>
<div><h2>Basic grep command:</h2></div>
<div><br></div>
<div><b>Match control</b><br></div>
<div><br></div>
<div>-e: recognises pattern as the regular expression argument</div>
<div>-f: takes patterns from a file. grep returns every line that</div>
<div>matches any pattern (additive)</div>
<div>   Ex: grep -f pattern.txt searchere.txt</div>
<div>-i: ignore case</div>
<div>-v: invert-match : return lines that do not match</div>
<div>-w: matched only when the input text consists of full words</div>
<div>-x: match the entire line</div>
<div><br></div>
<div><br></div>
<div><b>General output control</b><br></div>
<div><br></div>
<div>-c: just return counts of how many lines matched</div>
<div>-l: prints just the names of input files containing the pattern</div>
<div>-L: oposite to -l</div>
<div><br></div>
<div><br></div>
<div><h2>grep-Relevant Environment Variables</h2></div>
<div><br></div>
<div>-env: list out all env variables in your computer </div>
<div><br></div>
<div><br></div>
<div><h2>Searching through large numbers of files</h2></div>
<div><br></div>
<div>Ex1: grep some_pattern *: search for “some_pattern” in all files in the current folder —&gt but if there are too many files —&gt “Too many files” error</div>
<div><br></div>
<div>—&gt solution:</div>
<div>find / -print | xargs grep 'some_pattern'</div>
